# Go Code Quality Standards

## Complexity limits (CodeScene gates)

- **Cyclomatic complexity ≤ 8 per function.** If a function needs more than 8 decision points, it has more than one responsibility. Split it.
- **Cognitive complexity ≤ 10 per function.** Count every nesting level, every boolean operator, every break/continue.
- **Lines per function ≤ 40.** Count only non-blank, non-comment lines. Constructors and handlers that delegate are exempt up to 60 lines.
- **Lines per file ≤ 400.** A file that grows past 400 lines is absorbing too many concerns.
- **Parameters per function ≤ 4.** If you need more, introduce a config or options struct.
- **Nesting depth ≤ 3.** Flatten with early returns, extracted functions, or guard clauses.

## Interfaces — accept wide, return narrow

```go
// WRONG — accepts concrete type, locks callers in
func NewRateLimiter(client *redis.Client) *RedisSlider { ... }

// RIGHT — accepts interface, returns interface
// The concrete type is the implementation detail; callers own the interface.
func NewRedisSlider(client redis.UniversalClient) ratelimit.Limiter { ... }
```

Accept the narrowest interface your function needs. Return the most concrete type you have.
Never define an interface in the same package that implements it — that's not an abstraction, it's a mock target.

## Error handling — every error is handled or explicitly discarded

```go
// WRONG — ignoring errors silently
rows, _ := pool.Query(ctx, q, id)
defer rows.Close()

// WRONG — too generic, loses context
return fmt.Errorf("query failed: %w", err)

// RIGHT — wraps with operation context
return fmt.Errorf("AgentStore.GetByIDAndOrg orgID=%s agentID=%s: %w", orgID, agentID, err)
```

Full rules in `02-go-error-handling.mdc`.

## Struct design — no data clumps, no primitive obsession

```go
// WRONG — primitive obsession; which string is which?
func CreateToken(orgID, userID, name, description string, perms int64) error { ... }

// WRONG — data clump; these travel together, should be a type
orgID := ctx.Value("org_id").(string)
agentID := ctx.Value("agent_id").(string)

// RIGHT — options struct for >3 related params
type CreateTokenParams struct {
    OrgID       uuid.UUID
    UserID      uuid.UUID
    Name        string
    Description string
    Permissions permissions.Bitmap
    ExpiresAt   *time.Time // nil = non-expiring
}
func CreateToken(ctx context.Context, p CreateTokenParams) (string, error) { ... }

// RIGHT — typed IDs prevent mixing up org_id and agent_id
type OrgID   uuid.UUID
type AgentID uuid.UUID
```

## No global state

```go
// WRONG — global logger, hidden dependency
var log = slog.Default()

// WRONG — init() with side effects
func init() {
    prometheus.MustRegister(requestCounter)
}

// RIGHT — dependency injection; state is explicit
type Handler struct {
    store  AgentStore
    logger *logger.Logger
    tracer trace.Tracer
}
func NewHandler(store AgentStore, logger *logger.Logger, tracer trace.Tracer) *Handler { ... }
```

## Constants and magic values

```go
// WRONG — magic numbers
if count > 60 { return ErrRateLimited }
time.Sleep(30 * time.Second)

// RIGHT — named constants with units in name
const defaultRPMLimit = 60
const defaultShutdownTimeout = 30 * time.Second
```

## Receivers — consistent, short, non-generic

```go
// WRONG — this, self, s, srv (generic)
func (this *AgentStore) Get(...) {}
func (s *AgentStore) Get(...) {}  // 's' is ok only if the type is also one char

// RIGHT — 1-2 chars derived from the type name
func (as *AgentStore) Get(...) {}
func (p *Proxy) ServeHTTP(...) {}
func (r *RedisSlider) Check(...) {}
```

## defer — never in loops, careful with closures

```go
// WRONG — defer in loop; rows never closed until function returns
for _, id := range ids {
    rows, _ := pool.Query(ctx, q, id)
    defer rows.Close() // BUG: deferred, not called per iteration
    // ...
}

// RIGHT — extract to function or close explicitly
for _, id := range ids {
    if err := processOne(ctx, pool, id); err != nil {
        return err
    }
}

func processOne(ctx context.Context, pool *pgxpool.Pool, id uuid.UUID) error {
    rows, err := pool.Query(ctx, q, id)
    if err != nil { return err }
    defer rows.Close()
    // ...
    return rows.Err()
}
```

## No naked `any` / `interface{}`

```go
// WRONG — loses all type safety
func Set(key string, value interface{}) {}

// RIGHT — generics (Go 1.21+) or typed alternatives
func Set[T any](key string, value T) {}

// RIGHT — for context keys: unexported struct type, not string
type reqIDKey struct{}
ctx = context.WithValue(ctx, reqIDKey{}, id) // cannot collide with other keys
```

## Exported API surface is the contract — comment everything exported

Every exported function, type, constant, and variable must have a Go doc comment.
The comment explains WHY, not WHAT (the signature already says what).

```go
// WRONG — no comment
func (as *AgentStore) GetByIDAndOrg(ctx context.Context, agentID, orgID uuid.UUID) (*AgentRecord, error)

// WRONG — restates the signature
// GetByIDAndOrg gets an agent by ID and org.

// RIGHT — explains semantics, failure mode, and caller contract
// GetByIDAndOrg fetches a single agent and verifies it belongs to orgID.
// Returns (nil, nil) when the agent does not exist or belongs to a different
// org — the caller must map this to a 403, not a 404, to avoid leaking the
// existence of another org's resources.
func (as *AgentStore) GetByIDAndOrg(ctx context.Context, agentID, orgID uuid.UUID) (*AgentRecord, error)
```

## File organisation within a package

```text
internal/middleware/
  requestid.go       ← one concern per file
  requestid_test.go  ← test file adjacent to implementation
  auth.go
  auth_test.go
  ratelimit.go
  ratelimit_test.go
  context.go         ← shared context key types and accessors
```

Never put unrelated types in the same file because "they're small." Small is not a reason to co-locate. Shared types go in a dedicated `types.go` or `context.go`.
